gdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Skotsko, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"da":{"1310–1357":"1310–1357","1295–1346":"1295–1346","1300–Male":"1300–Afdød","1312–Male":"1312–Afdød","1310–Female":"1310–Afdød","1312–Female":"1312–Afdød","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1335–Male":"1335–Afdød","1276–1340":"1276–1340","1276–Female":"1276–Afdød","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","about 1335":"omkring 1335","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1380":"1380","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Skotland, United Kingdom","England":"England","Craigdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Craigdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Skotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Skotland"},"nl":{"1310–1357":"1310–1357","1295–1346":"1295–1346","1300–Male":"1300–Overleden","1312–Male":"1312–Overleden","1310–Female":"1310–Overleden","1312–Female":"1312–Overleden","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1335–Male":"1335–Overleden","1276–1340":"1276–1340","1276–Female":"1276–Overleden","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","about 1335":"circa 1335","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1380":"1380","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Craigdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Craigdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1310–1357":"1310–1357","1295–1346":"1295–1346","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1312–Male":"1312–Deceased","1310–Female":"1310–Deceased","1312–Female":"1312–Deceased","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1335–Male":"1335–Deceased","1276–1340":"1276–1340","1276–Female":"1276–Deceased","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1312":"1312","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1276":"1276","1330":"1330","about 1335":"about 1335","1340":"1340","1295":"1295","1380":"1380","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","England":"England","Craigdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Craigdarroch, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Kirkpatrick,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from either of two places in Dumfriess called Kirkpatrick or any of various other places in Scotland, all so named from the dedication of their church to Saint Patrick. The Scottish word <i>kirk</i> sometimes replaced Gaelic <i>cill</i> ‘church’ in placenames; compare   Kilpatrick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kilpatrick","meanings":["Irish (Ulster): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Phádraig</b> ‘son of the servant of (Saint) Patrick’ (Irish <i>Pádraig</i>). See also   Fitzpatrick  .","Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called in Gaelic as <i>cill Padraig</i> ‘church of (Saint) Patrick’. See also   Kirkpatrick  ."]}]},{"name":"second","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French   Sicard  , reflecting the characteristic Canadian and American French rounding of the <i>-ard</i> ending. Compare   Secor   and   Sicord  .","History: The Secords are descendants of Ambroise Sicard, a Huguenot refugee from France (see   Sicard  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Sicard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Adrien, Albertine, Aude, Benoit, Camille, Elzear, Francois, Jacques, Jean-Paul, Marcel, Monique, Numa.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sighard</i>, composed of the elements <i>sig</i> ‘victory’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hard, strong’. Compare   Seacord  ,   Secor  ,   Secord  ,   Secore  ,   Secoy  , and   Sicord  .","History: Jean Sicard from Mornac-sur-Seudre in Charente-Maritime, France, married Catherine Lauzon in Montreal, QC, in 1681. Jean-Baptiste Sicard, <i>sieur</i> de Carufel (see   Carufel  ), from Castres in Tarn, France, married Geneviève Raté in Saint-Pierre, Île d'Orléans, QC, in 1694. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with its altered forms <i>Sicord</i> and <i>Seacord</i>) and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America. The Huguenot ancestor was Ambroise Sicard from France, who arrived with his wife and children in NY in the 1680s via England. His descendants (also) bear the surnames <i>Seacord</i>, <i>Secor</i>, <i>Secord</i>, and <i>Secoy</i>."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>laford</i>, <i>louerd</i>, <i>lord</i> ‘lord, master’ (Old English <i>hlāford</i>), perhaps given to a someone who played the part of the lord or master of ceremonies in festival games.","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as a translation of the main element of Gaelic <b>Ó Tighearnaigh</b> (see   Tierney  ) and <b>Mac Thighearnáin</b> (see   McKiernan  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Laure</b>, a variant of the personal name   Laur   3."],"variants":[{"name":"Tierney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eamon, John Patrick, Brigid, Clodagh, Kieran, Michael Sean, Siobhan.","Irish: shortened form of <b>O'Tierney</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Tíghearnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Tighearnach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘lord, master’. The Gaelic name is sometimes ‘translated’ as English   Lord  . Compare   Tiernan  ."]},{"name":"Lords","meanings":["English: variant of   Lord  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Kirkpatrick, second Lord of Closeburn was born in 1310, in Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Kirkpatrick, was 34 and his mother, Kirkpatrick, was 35. He married Kirkpatrick. He died in 1357, in Caerlaverock, Dumfriesshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1310–1357":"1310–1357","1295–1346":"1295–1346","1300–Male":"1300–Surnud","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1310–Female":"1310–Surnud","1312–Female":"1312–Surnud","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1276–1340":"1276–1340","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1357":"1357","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","131